comments: Sometimes I wanted a more challenging one when I was bored with the repetitive nature of the easy ones. However, I mostly chose the easy ones because I did not have to think as much.

subject: 9r7ae1vknw
comments: When both outcomes increased I was more likely to pick the risky deck. When both outcomes decreased I was more likely to pick the safe deck as I wanted to guarantee that there would be less options to choose from. In general I was more likely to choose the safe deck.

comments: Don't gamble when green, gamble when  red

subject: ltyrxatoxa
comments: When all outcomes were decreases in objects I was more willing to take the risky deck than I was when all outcomes were increases. What drove my decision was wanting to choose the quickest option.

subject: 20gvzcsl3j
comments: I preferred when all outcomes were decreases in objects because it was easier to distinguish what was the target object and what was not the target object.

subject: vt5w63tdsrd
comments: Consistently throughout the blocks, I chose the card that had one lower option. Taking risks with the hopes that I would get a 0 would probably lead me to get frustrated or tired if I happened to land a +28. Consistency is reliable and the path worth taking. When all outcomes were decreases in objects, I chose the two option card when I got the feeling to, but overall only chose the one option card. Once again, consistency is important to getting through things.

subject: tccbf44h8j
comments: I felt like if I chose the deck with the single option I had a better chance of choosing the good option of the two option deck next time. I also usually picked the two-choice deck if it was decreasing the outcome because it's either 0 or less and I don't mind having 32 options.

subject: l3h29t9dzjb
comments: When the numbers were positive I would go risky because at that point there was already extra numbers. When the numbers were positive I still usually chose risky to try to make it really easy but I sometimes chose the safe route.
